msgid ":obj:`scipy.linalg.rq`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:66
msgid "Compute RQ decomposition of a matrix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:70
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:71
msgid ""
"When mode is 'reduced' or 'complete', the result will be a namedtuple with "
"the attributes ``Q`` and ``R``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:74
msgid ""
"This is an interface to the LAPACK routines ``dgeqrf``, ``zgeqrf``, "
"``dorgqr``, and ``zungqr``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:77
msgid ""
"For more information on the qr factorization, see for example: https://en."
"wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_factorization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:80
msgid ""
"Subclasses of `ndarray` are preserved except for the 'raw' mode. So if `a` "
"is of type `matrix`, all the return values will be matrices too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:83
msgid ""
"New 'reduced', 'complete', and 'raw' options for mode were added in NumPy "
"1.8.0 and the old option 'full' was made an alias of 'reduced'.  In addition "
"the options 'full' and 'economic' were deprecated.  Because 'full' was the "
"previous default and 'reduced' is the new default, backward compatibility "
"can be maintained by letting `mode` default. The 'raw' option was added so "
"that LAPACK routines that can multiply arrays by q using the Householder "
"reflectors can be used. Note that in this case the returned arrays are of "
"type np.double or np.cdouble and the h array is transposed to be FORTRAN "
"compatible.  No routines using the 'raw' return are currently exposed by "
"numpy, but some are available in lapack_lite and just await the necessary "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:97
msgid "Examples"
msgstr "範例"

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:120
msgid ""
"Example illustrating a common use of `qr`: solving of least squares problems"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:123
msgid ""
"What are the least-squares-best `m` and `y0` in ``y = y0 + mx`` for the "
"following data: {(0,1), (1,0), (1,2), (2,1)}. (Graph the points and you'll "
"see that it should be y0 = 0, m = 1.)  The answer is provided by solving the "
"over-determined matrix equation ``Ax = b``, where::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:128
msgid ""
"A = array([[0, 1], [1, 1], [1, 1], [2, 1]])\n"
"x = array([[y0], [m]])\n"
"b = array([[1], [0], [2], [1]])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.qr:132
msgid ""
"If A = QR such that Q is orthonormal (which is always possible via Gram-"
"Schmidt), then ``x = inv(R) * (Q.T) * b``.  (In numpy practice, however, we "
"simply use `lstsq`.)"
msgstr ""

